text: Dystonia 16 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and multifocal dystonia, which specifically has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a multifocal dystonia characterized by early-onset progressive limb dystonia, laryngeal and oromandibular dystonia, and parkinsonism. This disease has its material basis in the autosomal recessive inheritance of a homozygous mutation in the protein activator of interferon-induced protein kinase EIF2AK2 (PRKRA) gene located on chromosome 2q31.

Paroxysmal nonkinesigenic dyskinesia 1 is classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of dystonia. It is associated with a condition that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is influenced by factors such as alcohol. This dystonia is defined by episodes of dystonic or choreathetotic movements triggered by stress, fatigue, coffee or alcohol intake, or menstruation. Its genetic foundation lies in the autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the PNKD metallo-beta-lactamase domain-containing gene located on chromosome 2q35.

Dystonia 27 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, segmental dystonia, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a segmental dystonia characterized by the autosomal recessive inheritance of segmental isolated dystonia, primarily affecting the craniocervical region and upper limbs with onset in the first 2 decades of life. This condition has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of compound heterozygous mutations in the collagen type VI alpha-3 gene on chromosome 2q37.

Dystonia 23 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of focal dystonia, which at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a focal dystonia characterized by adult-onset cervical dystonia typically occurring in the fourth or fifth decade of life. This condition is due to the autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the CACNA1B gene on chromosome 9q34.

Dystonia 24 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of focal dystonia, which at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a focal dystonia characterized by affecting the neck, laryngeal muscles, and muscles of the upper limbs. This condition has a material basis in the autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the anoctamin 3 (ANO3) gene on chromosome 11p14.

Episodic kinesigenic dyskinesia 1 is classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease, dystonia, and a condition that has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a dystonia characterized by recurrent brief involuntary hyperkinesias triggered by sudden movements, which results from the autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the proline-rich transmembrane protein 2 gene (PRRT2) on chromosome 16p11. Additionally, episodic kinesigenic dyskinesia 1 is also exactly synonymous with Paroxysmal kinesigenic choreoathetosis.

Episodic kinesigenic dyskinesia 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of dystonia, which is characterized by a specific kind that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a dystonia that features recurrent brief involuntary hyperkinesias triggered by sudden movements, and this condition has a material basis in the autosomal dominant inheritance of variation in the chromosome region 16q13-q22.1.

Dystonia 25 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of multifocal dystonia, which is also defined as a multifocal dystonia characterized by cervical, laryngeal, and hand-forearm dystonia. This condition has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance, specifically, it is due to the autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the GNAL gene on chromosome 18p11.

Dystonia 12 is a type of dystonia and an autosomal dominant disease, which means it has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is characterized by asymmetric dystonia and parkinsonism with an abrupt onset in young adulthood. This condition is attributed to autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding the alpha-3 subunit of the N,K-ATPase (ATP1A3) located on chromosome 19q13.

X-linked dystonia parkinsonism is a type of focal dystonia and also a type of X-linked recessive disease, which at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as a focal dystonia characterized by parkinsonism that is frequently accompanied by focal dystonia and progresses to generalized dystonia. This condition has a material basis in the X-linked recessive inheritance of SVA retrotransposon insertion in the intron of the TATA-box binding protein associated factor 1 gene (TAF1) on chromosome Xq13.1.

Torsion dystonia with onset in infancy is a type of generalized dystonia, which is a type of autosomal dominant disease, and it is also a type of something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and at least starts during some infantile onset. It is defined as a generalized dystonia characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance with severe involvement of the legs, mild involvement of the face and arms, and onset in infancy.

Enhanced S cone syndrome is a type of retinal disease and an autosomal recessive disease, which essentially means it is a condition that notably has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a retinal disease characterized by early onset night blindness, hypersensitivity to blue light, and, in some cases, more general retinal degeneration. This degeneration has a material basis in the autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the nuclear receptor subfamily 2, group E, member 3 gene (NR2E3) on chromosome 15q23.

Wolcott Rallison Syndrome is a type of syndrome and autosomal recessive disease. It is known for having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and features symptoms such as hepatic dysfunction. The syndrome is defined as one characterized by permanent neonatal diabetes mellitus with multiple epiphyseal dysplasia, osteoporosis, growth retardation, and frequently hepatic and renal dysfunction. This condition is caused by homozygous mutations in the eukaryotic translation initiation factor 2 alpha kinase 3 (EIF2AK3) gene located on chromosome 2p11.2.

Familial cold autoinflammatory syndrome is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease that is defined as a primary immunodeficiency disease characterized by recurrent episodes of maculopapular skin rash triggered by exposure to cold, associated with low-grade fever, general malaise, eye redness, and arthralgia/myalgia. Additionally, familial cold autoinflammatory syndrome has the exact synonym FCAS.

Familial cold autoinflammatory syndrome 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and familial cold autoinflammatory syndrome, which is essentially a condition that has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is specifically characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the NLRP gene on chromosome 1q44, providing a detailed definition of this syndrome.

Familial Cold Autoinflammatory Syndrome 2 (FCAS2) is a type of familial cold autoinflammatory syndrome, which falls under autosomal dominant diseases. It is defined as a familial cold autoinflammatory syndrome characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance with a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the NLRP12 gene on chromosome 19q13. Additionally, FCAS2 is exactly synonymous with NLRP12-associated hereditary periodic fever syndrome.

Familial cold autoinflammatory syndrome 3 (FCAS3) is a specific type of familial cold autoinflammatory syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized as a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, FCAS3 is defined by the development of cutaneous urticaria, erythema, and pruritus in response to cold exposure. The genetic basis of FCAS3 involves a heterozygous deletion within the PLCG2 gene located on chromosome 16q.

Familial cold autoinflammatory syndrome 4 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of familial cold autoinflammatory syndrome, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by episodic high fevers, urticaria-like rash, and arthralgias starting at 2-3 months of age, often induced by cold exposure, and has a material basis in the autosomal dominant inheritance of heterozygous mutation in the NLRC4 gene on chromosome 2p22.
Fanconi-like syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by pancytopenia, immune deficiency, and cutaneous malignancies.

Fuhrmann syndrome is a type of disease related to bone development, specifically characterized by the bowing of the femora, aplasia or hypoplasia of the fibulae, and various forms of syndactyly including poly-, oligo-, and syndactyly. This condition fundamentally has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, particularly through the autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous mutations in the Wnt family member 7A (WNT7A) gene located on chromosome 3p25.

Giant axonal neuropathy 1 is a type of axonal neuropathy and an autosomal recessive disease, which is defined as an axonal neuropathy characterized by progressive motor and sensitive peripheral, central nervous system neuropathy, with axonal loss and giant axonal swellings filled with neurofilaments. It has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, particularly through homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the gigaxonin (GAN) gene on chromosome 16q23. This condition is also categorized as something that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Giant axonal neuropathy 2 is an autosomal dominant disease that falls under the category of axonal neuropathies. This condition involves a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is associated with symptoms such as muscle weakness. It is defined as an axonal neuropathy characterized by distal sensory impairment, lower extremity muscle weakness and atrophy, alongside giant axonal swelling with neurofilament accumulation. The genetic basis for this disorder is a heterozygous mutation in the DDB1- and CUL4-associated factor 8 (DCAF8) gene located on chromosome 1q23.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism is a type of hypogonadism characterized by impaired signaling by gonadotropin-releasing hormone. It is also known by exact synonyms such as congenital idiopathic hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, hypogonadotropism, and isolated congenital gonadotropin deficiency.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 11 with or without anosmia is a specific form of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, characterized as an autosomal recessive disease. This condition is also recognized as a type of disorder that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Furthermore, it is defined by a hypogonadotropic hypogonadism that originates from a homozygous mutation in the TACR3 gene located on chromosome 4q24.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 12 with or without anosmia is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is defined by a hypogonadotropic hypogonadism that arises due to a homozygous mutation in the GNRH1 gene located on chromosome 8p21. Additionally, it is also known by its exact synonyms, familial hypogonadotrophic eunuchoidism and familial idiopathic gonadotropin deficiency.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 13 with or without anosmia is a form of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism and is classified as an autosomal recessive disease. It is recognized as a condition that arises due to autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this type of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism is characterized by having its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the KISS1 gene located on chromosome 1q32.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 8 with or without anosmia is a type of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism and an autosomal recessive disease, which is characterized by a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a hypogonadotropic hypogonadism that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the KISS1R gene on chromosome 19p13, sometimes in association with mutation in other genes.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 15 with or without anosmia is identified as a type of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism and also as a form of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This specific type of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism is defined by having a material basis in a mutation in the HS6ST1 gene located on chromosome 2q14, which may sometimes be associated with mutations in other genes.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 18 with or without anosmia is classified as a type of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism. It is identified both as an autosomal dominant disease and as an autosomal recessive disease, indicating that it can have a material basis in either autosomal dominant or autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 18 with or without anosmia points out that it is a form of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism characterized by having its material basis in either heterozygous or homozygous mutation in the IL17RD gene located on chromosome 3p14, which may occur sometimes in conjunction with mutations in other genes.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 4 with or without anosmia is a specific type of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This condition is defined by a hypogonadotropic hypogonadism that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the prokineticin-2 gene (PROK2) on chromosome 3p13, which may sometimes be associated with a mutation in another gene.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 7 with or without anosmia is a type of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism and an autosomal recessive disease that is characterized by a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a hypogonadotropic hypogonadism that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GNRHR gene on chromosome 4q13, sometimes in association with a mutation in another gene. Notably, there have been no reported cases of patients with anosmia associated with this condition.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 17 with or without anosmia is a type of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this form of hypogonadism is defined by having a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SPRY4 gene located on chromosome 5q31, which may sometimes be associated with mutations in other genes.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 16 with or without anosmia is categorized as a type of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism and an autosomal dominant disease. It specifically involves a condition that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This particular form of hypogonadism is defined by having its material basis in a mutation in the SEMA3A gene on chromosome 7, which may sometimes occur in association with mutations in other genes.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 22 with or without anosmia is a type of autosomal recessive disease and hypogonadotropic hypogonadism. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and specifically has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the FEZF1 gene on chromosome 7q31.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 20 with or without anosmia is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a form of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, which is characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a hypogonadotropic hypogonadism that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the FGF17 gene on chromosome 8p21, occasionally in conjunction with mutations in other genes.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 2 with or without anosmia is a type of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism and an autosomal dominant disease. It can also be described as a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. This specific type of hypogonadism is defined as having a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the FGFR1 gene on chromosome 8p11, which may sometimes be associated with mutations in other genes.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 5 with or without anosmia is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism. It is characterized by something that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This condition is defined as a hypogonadotropic hypogonadism characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance and has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CHD7 gene on chromosome 8q12.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 9 with or without anosmia is a type of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized as a condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a hypogonadotropic hypogonadism characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance and has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the NELF gene on chromosome 9q34, which may sometimes be in association with a mutation in another gene.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 6 with or without anosmia is a type of autosomal dominant disease and hypogonadotropic hypogonadism. It is characterized by having at least a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined as a hypogonadotropic hypogonadism that features autosomal dominant inheritance and is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the FGF8 gene on chromosome 10q24, which can sometimes be associated with a mutation in another gene.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 14 with or without anosmia is a type of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a condition that has at least a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined as a hypogonadotropic hypogonadism that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the WDR11 gene on chromosome 10q26.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 24 without anosmia is a type of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism and an autosomal recessive disease, which specifically has its material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is defined by a hypogonadotropic hypogonadism that arises from either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the FSHB gene located on chromosome 11p14. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with isolated follicle-stimulating hormone deficiency.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 10 with or without anosmia is classified under several categories: it is a type of autosomal recessive disease, a form of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, and it is also considered a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined by a hypogonadotropic hypogonadism that originates from a homozygous mutation in the TAC3 gene located on chromosome 12q13.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 19 with or without anosmia is a subtype of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism and falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. The definition of this specific type of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism includes having a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the DUSP6 gene located on chromosome 12q22, which may sometimes be associated with mutations in other genes.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 23 with or without anosmia is a type of autosomal recessive disease, hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Its definition is a hypogonadotropic hypogonadism that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the LHB gene on chromosome 19q13. This condition is also known by several exact synonyms: 46,XY DSD due to LHB deficiency, 46,XY DSD due to luteinizing hormone subunit beta deficiency, 46,XY disorder of sex development due to LHB deficiency, 46,XY disorder of sex development due to luteinizing hormone subunit beta deficiency, Leydig cell hypoplasia due to luteinizing hormone subunit beta deficiency, Pasqualini syndrome, fertile eunuch syndrome, and Leydig cell hypoplasia due to LHB deficiency.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 3 with or without anosmia is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, which is characterized by a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a hypogonadotropic hypogonadism that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PROKR2 gene on chromosome 20p12, sometimes in association with a mutation in another gene.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 21 with or without anosmia is a specific type of autosomal dominant disease and is also categorized under hypogonadotropic hypogonadism. This condition is characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a hypogonadotropic hypogonadism that originates from a heterozygous mutation in the FLRT3 gene located on chromosome 20p11, which may sometimes occur in conjunction with mutations in other genes.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 1 with or without anosmia is a type of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism and is also categorized as a type of X-linked recessive disease, indicating that it has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. This condition is defined as a hypogonadotropic hypogonadism that results from a mutation in the KAL1 gene on chromosome Xp22.3, which may sometimes occur in association with a mutation in another gene. Additionally, hypogonadotropic hypogonadism 1 with or without anosmia is exactly synonymous with dysplasia olfactogenitalis of de Morsier.

Ocular albinism with sensorineural deafness is a subtype of ocular albinism 1, autosomal dominant disease, and digenic disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance and digenic inheritance. Specifically, ocular albinism with sensorineural deafness is defined as an ocular albinism that is characterized by deafness and vestibular dysfunction, with its material basis in the digenic inheritance of mutations in the transcription factor gene MITF on chromosome 3p13 and in the tyrosinase TYR gene on chromosome 11q14.3, which MITF regulates. Additionally, ocular albinism with sensorineural deafness is exactly synonymous with WS2-OA, autosomal recessive Waardenburg syndrome type 2 with ocular albinism, digenic Waardenburg syndrome/albinism, and digenic Waardenburg syndrome/ocular albinism.

The Lethal Congenital Glycogen Storage Disease of Heart is categorized as a type of physical disorder, specifically a variant of glycogen storage disease. It is also recognized as a condition that fundamentally arises from some form of abnormality related to prenatal development or birth, and is linked to a structural variant. This disease is defined by glycogenosis confined to the heart, accompanied by hypoglycemia and cyanosis, and is caused by an autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding the noncatalytic gamma-2 subunit of AMP-activated protein kinase (PRKAG2) located on chromosome 7q36. Furthermore, it is known under several exact synonyms, including Fatal Congenital Hypertrophic Cardiomyopathy due to GSD, Fatal Congenital Hypertrophic Cardiomyopathy due to Glycogenosis, Fatal Congenital Nonlysosomal Cardiac Glycogenosis, and Phosphorylase Kinase Deficiency of Heart.

Autosomal dominant macrothrombocytopenia TUBB1 related is a type of autosomal dominant disease, thrombocytopenia, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a thrombocytopenia characterized by macrothrombocytopenia with normal platelet aggregation and has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance of mutations in the tubulin beta-1 (TUBB1) gene on chromosome 20q13.3.

Huntington's disease like 1 is a type of prion disease characterized by a phenocopy of Huntington disease, which includes unwanted choreatic movements, behavioral and psychiatric disturbances, and dementia. This condition has a material basis in the autosomal dominant inheritance of 8 extra octapeptide repeats in the prion protein (PRNP) gene on chromosome 20p13. It has several exact synonyms, including HDL1, HLN1, Huntington disease-like 1, Huntington-like neurodegenerative disorder 1, autosomal dominant Huntington-like neurodegenerative disorder, and early-onset prion disease with prominent psychiatric features.

Huntington's Disease-Like 2 (HDL2), also known exactly as Huntington Disease-Like 2, is a type of neurodegenerative disease. This disease is characterized by symptoms such as weight loss and dementia, indicating its complex impact on health. Specifically, Huntington's Disease-Like 2 is defined as a neurodegenerative condition marked by involuntary movements, abnormalities in voluntary movements, psychiatric symptoms, weight loss, and dementia. These symptoms typically begin in the fourth decade of life, leading to death about 20 years after onset. The disease's genetic basis involves autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous expansion of a CAG/CTG repeat in the junctophilin-3 gene (JPH3) on chromosome 16q24.

Autosomal recessive hypercholesterolemia is a type of familial hypercholesterolemia, which also falls under a category of diseases that are based on some structural variant. This condition is defined as a familial hypercholesterolemia characterized by very high levels of low-density lipoprotein (LDL) cholesterol, usually above 400 mg/dl, and an increased risk of premature atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease. It has its material basis in autosomal recessive homozygous mutations in the low-density lipoprotein receptor adaptor protein 1 gene (LDLRAP1) on chromosome 1p36. Furthermore, autosomal recessive hypercholesterolemia is exactly synonymous with ARH, ARH1, ARH2, FHCB1, FHCB2, autosomal recessive hypercholesterolemia 1, autosomal recessive hypercholesterolemia 2, and familial autosomal recessive hypercholesterolemia.

BH4 deficient hyperphenylalaninemia A is a type of autosomal recessive disease, tetrahydrobiopterin (BH4) deficient hyperphenylalaninemia, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a tetrahydrobiopterin (BH4)-deficient hyperphenylalaninemia characterized by hyperphenylalaninemia, depletion of the neurotransmitters dopamine and serotonin, and progressive cognitive and motor deficits. This condition has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of a mutation in the gene encoding 6-pyruvoyl-tetrahydropterin synthase (PTS) on chromosome 11q23.1. It is also known by several exact synonyms: 6-pyruvoyl-tetrahydropterin synthase deficiency, HPABH4A, PTS deficiency, hyperphenylalaninemia due to 6-pyruvoyltetrahydropterin synthase deficiency, and tetrahydrobiopterin-deficient hyperphenylalaninemia due to PTS deficiency.

Autosomal dominant hypocalcemia 1 is a type of autosomal dominant hypocalcemia and is defined as an autosomal dominant hypocalcemia disease that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the calcium sensing receptor gene (CASR) on chromosome 3q21. Additionally, it has the exact synonym HYPOC1.

Autosomal dominant hypocalcemia 2 is a type of autosomal dominant hypocalcemia and has an exact synonym, HYPOC2. It is defined as an autosomal dominant hypocalcemia that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the G protein subunit alpha 11 gene (GNA11) on chromosome 19p13.

Autosomal dominant hypocalcemia is classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of metal metabolism disorder. It is further categorized as something that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. The condition is defined as a metal metabolism disorder characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of variable degrees of hypocalcemia with normal to low levels of parathyroid hormone. Additionally, it is precisely synonymous with HYPOC.

Immune dysregulation polyendocrinopathy enteropathy X-linked (IPEX) syndrome is a type of autoimmune disease, which is also categorized as an X-linked recessive disease. This condition is based on X-linked recessive inheritance and it manifests symptoms including diarrhea. It is defined as an autoimmune disease characterized by the onset in infancy of refractory diarrhea, endocrinopathies, type 1 diabetes mellitus, and dermatitis, which has its material basis in an X-linked recessive mutation in the forkhead box P3 (FOXP3) gene on chromosome Xp11. IPEX syndrome is known by several exact synonyms, including Autoimmune enteropathy type 1, DMSD, IDDM-secretory diarrhea syndrome, X-linked autoimmunity-allergic dysregulation syndrome, XLAAD, XPID, autoimmunity-immunodeficiency syndrome, X-linked, diabetes mellitus, congenital insulin-dependent, with fatal secretory diarrhea, diarrhea, polyendocrinopathy, fatal infection syndrome, X-linked, immunodeficiency, polyendocrinopathy, and enteropathy, X-linked, and immunodysregulation, polyendocrinopathy, and enteropathy, X-Linked.

PCWH syndrome is a type of syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases and is characterized by the association of the features of Waardenburg-Shah syndrome (sensorineural hearing loss, pigmentary abnormalities, and Hirschsprung disease) with neurological features, including neonatal hypotonia, intellectual deficit (of variable severity), nystagmus, progressive spasticity, ataxia, and epilepsy. This syndrome has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the SRY-box 10 (SOX10) gene on chromosome 22q13. PCWH syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms including Neurologic Waardenburg-Shah syndrome, PCWH, Peripheral Demyelinating Neuropathy, Central Dysmyelination, Waardenburg Syndrome, and Hirschsprung Disease, as well as Peripheral demyelinating neuropathy-central dysmyelinating leukodystrophy-Hirschsprung disease-Waardenburg syndrome.

Nasu Hakola disease is a syndrome that is also known as NHD, PLO-SL, PLOSL, polycystic lipomembranous osteodysplasia with sclerosing leukoencephalopathy, presenile dementia with bone cysts, and progressive dementia with lipomembranous polycystic osteodysplasia; brain-bone-fat disease. It is characterized by a type of autosomal recessive disease and has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined by a syndrome that involves progressive presenile dementia and recurrent bone fractures due to polycystic osseous lesions of the lower and upper extremities, resulting from homozygous mutations in the TYRO protein tyrosine kinase binding protein (TYROBP) gene on chromosome 19q13 or homozygous mutations in the triggering receptor expressed on myeloid cells 2 (TREM2) gene on chromosome 6p21.

Riddle syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and syndrome, which essentially has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by increased radiosensitivity, immunodeficiency, mild motor control and learning difficulties, facial dysmorphism, and short stature. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ring finger protein 168 (RNF168) gene located on chromosome 3q29. Additionally, Riddle syndrome is precisely known by two exact synonyms: RNF168 deficiency and Radiosensitivity-immunodeficiency-dysmorphic features-learning difficulties syndrome.

Sorsby's fundus dystrophy is a type of autosomal dominant disease, hereditary retinal dystrophy, and is characterized by aspects that are inherently related to autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is a hereditary retinal dystrophy that leads to the loss of central vision due to macular disease by the fourth to fifth decade and results in peripheral visual loss later in life. This condition is rooted in the autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the TIMP metallopeptidase inhibitor 3 (TIMP3) gene on chromosome 22q12. Additionally, Sorsby's fundus dystrophy is also known by several exact synonyms including SFD, hemorrhagic macular dystrophy, and pseudoinflammatory fundus dystrophy of Sorsby.

Spinocerebellar ataxia with axonal neuropathy 1 (SCAN1), also known exactly as autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia with axonal neuropathy 1 and spinocerebellar ataxia with axonal neuropathy type 1, is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia. It is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of spinocerebellar ataxia and peripheral neuropathy, with the disease having a material basis in homozygosity for a mutation in the TDP1 gene on chromosome 14q32.11. Furthermore, SCAN1 is also considered a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Spondylocarpotarsal synostosis syndrome is a type of disease that falls under several categories: it is an autosomal recessive disease, a spinal disease, and a bone development disease. It is characterized by a condition that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and has its location in the vertebral column. The syndrome is defined as a bone development disease that progresses postnatally with frequent manifestations of block vertebrae, leading to an undersized trunk, disproportionate short stature, scoliosis, lordosis, carpal and tarsal synostosis, club feet, and mild facial dysmorphism. This condition is caused by autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the filamin B (FLNB) gene on chromosome 3p14.3. Spondylocarpotarsal synostosis syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms including SCT, congenital scoliosis with unilateral unsegmented bar, congenital synspondylism, spondylocarpotarsal syndrome, spondylocarpotarsal synostosis, and vertebral fusion with carpal coalition.

Thiamine responsive megaloblastic anemia syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by megaloblastic anemia, non-type I diabetes mellitus, and sensorineural deafness where the anemia, and sometimes diabetes, is responsive to high doses of thiamine. The syndrome has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the solute carrier family 19 member 2 (SLC19A2) gene on chromosome 1q24. This syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms: Rogers syndrome, THMD1, TRMA, thiamine metabolism dysfunction syndrome 1, thiamine-responsive anaemia syndrome, thiamine-responsive anemia syndrome, thiamine-responsive megaloblastic anaemia syndrome, thiamine-responsive megaloblastic anaemia with diabetes mellitus and sensorineural deafness, thiamine-responsive megaloblastic anemia with diabetes mellitus and sensorineural deafness, and thiamine-responsive myelodysplasia.

Congenital amegakaryocytic thrombocytopenia (CAMT), also known as congenital amegakaryocytic thrombocytopenic purpura, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, physical disorder, and thrombocytopenia. It is characterized by a severe reduction in megakaryocyte and platelet numbers. This condition has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the myeloproliferative leukemia virus oncogene (MPL) on chromosome 1p34. Furthermore, it is defined as a disorder that at least has its basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance and is related to an abnormality of prenatal development or birth.

Ankyloblepharon ectodermal defects cleft lip palate syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease, ectodermal dysplasia, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an ectodermal dysplasia characterized by ankyloblepharon filiforme adnatum and cleft lip and palate, which has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the tumor protein p63 (TP63) gene on chromosome 3q27. This syndrome is also precisely known as AEC syndrome, Hay-Wells syndrome, and ankyloblepharon-ectodermal defects-cleft lip and palate syndrome.

Hereditary neutrophilia is a type of leukocyte disease that is categorized as an autosomal dominant disease and is characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a leukocyte disease marked by autosomal dominant inheritance of lifelong, persistent elevated neutrophil counts primarily consisting of segmented neutrophils. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the colony-stimulating factor 3 receptor (CSF3R) gene located on chromosome 1p34.

Aromatase excess syndrome is a type of reproductive system disease characterized by increased extraglandular aromatization of steroids, leading to heterosexual precocity in males and isosexual precocity in females. This condition has a material basis in the autosomal dominant inheritance of the fusion of the aromatase gene (CYP19A1) with various partners, caused by translocations and resulting in a gain of function of the CYP19A1 gene. It is also exactly synonymous with AEXS, familial hyperestrogenism, hereditary prepubertal gynecomastia, and increased aromatase activity.

Aromatic L amino acid decarboxylase deficiency, also known exactly as AADC deficiency, is an inherited metabolic disorder. This disorder manifests with symptoms including ptosis and is rooted in structural variants. It is characterized by a reduced production of serotonin and dopamine, leading to hypotonia, hypokinesia, ptosis, oculogyric crises, and signs of autonomic dysfunction. The material basis of this condition lies in autosomal recessive inheritance, specifically through homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the dopa decarboxylase gene (DDC) located on chromosome 7p12.

Neurogenic type arthrogryposis multiplex congenita 2 is a specific type of arthrogryposis multiplex congenita and also falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This particular disorder is defined by its manifestation of congenital contractures at the elbows and knees, myopathy, the absence of muscle spindles, congenital heart disease, and spinal motor neuron depletion. It specifically arises from the autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous mutations in the endoplasmic reticulum-golgi intermediate compartment protein 1 gene (ERGIC1) located on chromosome region 5q35. Furthermore, this condition is known by several exact synonyms, including AMC neurogenic type, AMC2, AMCN, arthrogryposis multiplex congenita 2, neurogenic type, and arthrogryposis multiplex congenita neurogenic type.

Brain Small Vessel Disease 1 (BSVD1) is a specific type of brain small vessel disease and an autosomal dominant disease. It is defined by fragile small blood vessels in the brain, leukoencephalopathy, an increased risk of stroke, seizure, migraine, and in some cases, Axenfeld-Riegar anomaly. This condition is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance, specifically through a heterozygous mutation in the collagen type IV alpha 1 chain gene (COL4A1) located on chromosome 13q34.

BSVD1 is also known by several exact synonyms, including COL4A1-related brain small vessel disease with hemorrhage, COL4A1-related familial vascular leukoencephalopathy, COL4A1-related retinal arteriolar tortuosity-infantile hemiparesis-autosomal dominant leukoencephalopathy syndrome, autosomal dominant retinal arteriolar tortuosity, infantile hemiparesis, and leukencephalopathy, brain small vessel disease with Axenfeld-Riegar anomaly, brain small vessel disease with hemorrhage, brain small vessel disease with or without ocular anomalies, infantile hemiparesis, and leukoencephalopathy with Axenfeld-Riegar anomaly.

Branched chain keto acid dehydrogenase kinase deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease, amino acid metabolic disorder, and is associated with material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an amino acid metabolic disorder characterized by autism, epilepsy, intellectual disability, and reduced levels of branched-chain amino acids due to a homozygous mutation in the branched chain keto acid dehydrogenase kinase gene (BCKDK) on chromosome 16p11. This condition is also exactly synonymous with BCKDK deficiency, BCKDKD, and autism-epilepsy syndrome due to branched chain ketoacid dehydrogenase kinase deficiency.

Camptodactyly arthropathy coxa vara pericarditis syndrome is an autosomal recessive disease and a syndrome that exhibits a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, possibly involving a homozygous mutation in the proteoglycan 4 gene (PRG4) on chromosome 1q31. This syndrome is characterized by congenital or early-onset camptodactyly, noninflammatory arthropathy with synovial hyperplasia, and in some patients, progressive coxa vara deformity, and/or noninflammatory pericardial or pleural effusion. It also has a symptom of pericardial effusion. The syndrome is known by several exact synonyms, including CACP, CACP syndrome, CAP syndrome, Jacobs syndrome, PAC syndrome, arthropathy-camptodactyly syndrome, camptodactyly-arthropathy-pericarditis syndrome, congenital familial hypertrophic synovitis, familial fibrosing serositis, and pericarditis-arthropathy-camptodactyly syndrome.

Carvajal syndrome is a type of Naxos disease, characterized by dilated cardiomyopathy, woolly hair, and keratoderma. This condition has a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the desmoplakin gene on chromosome 6p24. Carvajal syndrome is also exactly synonymous with DCWHK, dilated cardiomyopathy with woolly hair and keratoderma, and palmoplantar keratoderma with left ventricular cardiomyopathy and woolly hair.

Carnitine Palmitoyltransferase I Deficiency is a disorder characterized by a lipid metabolism anomaly. It falls under the category of diseases that have their basis in some structural variant. Specifically, this condition is defined by the impaired mitochondrial oxidation of long chain fatty acids in the liver and kidneys, leading to episodes of illness- or fasting-induced hypoketotic hypoglycemia. This disorder is caused by autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the carnitine palmitoyltransferase 1A gene (CPT1A) on chromosome 11q13. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including CPT I Deficiency, CPT1A Deficiency, L-CPT1 Deficiency, Carnitine Palmitoyl Transferase 1A Deficiency, Carnitine Palmitoyl Transferase IA Deficiency, Hepatic CPT Deficiency Type I, Hepatic Carnitine Palmitoyl Transferase 1 Deficiency, and Hepatic Carnitine Palmitoyl Transferase I Deficiency.

Cortical Dysplasia Focal Epilepsy Syndrome (CDFE Syndrome), also known exactly as CDFES, PTHSL1, and Pitt-Hopkins-like syndrome-1, is categorized as a type of autosomal recessive disease, specifically a brain disease. This condition is characterized by cortical dysplasia, focal epilepsy, macrocephaly, and diminished deep-tendon reflexes. Its material basis can be traced to autosomal recessive inheritance involving either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the contactin associated protein-like 2 (CNTNAP2) gene on chromosome 7q35-q36.

Complex cortical dysplasia with other brain malformations (CDCBM) is classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease, brain disease, and something that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Additionally, it is defined as a brain disease characterized by aberrant neuronal migration and disturbed axonal guidance, leading to various brain malformations.

Complex cortical dysplasia with other brain malformations 7 is a type of complex cortical dysplasia with other brain malformations that is characterized by abnormalities in cortical brain development. This condition has a material basis in the autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the tubulin beta 2B class IIb (TUBB2B) gene on chromosome 6p25. It is also exactly synonymous with CDCBM7 and polymicrogyria due to TUBB2B mutation.

Complex cortical dysplasia with other brain malformations 2 is a type of complex cortical dysplasia with other brain malformations. It is defined as a complex cortical dysplasia with other brain malformations that has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the kinesin family member 5C (KIF5C) gene on chromosome 2q23. Furthermore, complex cortical dysplasia with other brain malformations 2 is exactly synonymous with CDCBM2.

Complex cortical dysplasia with other brain malformations 3 (CDCBM3) is a type of complex cortical dysplasia with other brain malformations. It is characterized by a condition that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance of heterozygous mutation in the kinesin family member 2A (KIF2A) gene on chromosome 5q12.

Complex cortical dysplasia with other brain malformations 5 (CDCBM5) is a type of complex cortical dysplasia with other brain malformations. It is characterized by a complex cortical dysplasia with other brain malformations that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the tubulin beta 2A class IIa (TUBB2A) gene located on chromosome 6p25.

Complex cortical dysplasia with other brain malformations 6 is a type of complex cortical dysplasia with other brain malformations. It is defined as a complex cortical dysplasia with other brain malformations that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the tubulin beta class I (TUBB) gene on chromosome 6p21. Furthermore, it has an exact synonym, CDCBM56.

Complex cortical dysplasia with other brain malformations 1 is a type of complex cortical dysplasia with other brain malformations characterized by a complex cortical dysplasia with other brain malformations that arises from autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the tubulin beta 3 class III (TUBB3) gene on chromosome 16q24.3. It is also precisely known by two exact synonyms: CDCBM1 and cortical dysgenesis with pontocerebellar hypoplasia due to TUBB3 mutation.

Complex cortical dysplasia with other brain malformations 4 is a type of complex cortical dysplasia with other brain malformations, which has an exact synonym, CDCBM4. This condition is defined as a complex cortical dysplasia with other brain malformations that has its material basis in the autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the tubulin gamma 1 gene on chromosome 17q21.

Cortisone reductase deficiency is a type of endocrine system disease characterized by the failure to regenerate the active glucocorticoid cortisol from cortisone, resulting in adrenal hyperandrogenism. It also has the exact synonym CORTRD.

Cortisone reductase deficiency 2 (CORTRD2) is a type of autosomal dominant disease, specifically a form of cortisone reductase deficiency, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by a failure to regenerate cortisol via the enzyme 11-beta-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase, leading to ACTH-mediated adrenal hyperandrogenism. This condition is due to an autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the 11-beta-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase type I (HSD11B1) gene located on chromosome 1q32.

Cortisone reductase deficiency 1 (CORTRD1) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of cortisone reductase deficiency. It is characterized by the inability to regenerate cortisol due to the failure of the enzyme 11-beta-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase, which requires NADPH regeneration by hexose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase. This deficiency leads to ACTH-mediated adrenal hyperandrogenism. The condition has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the hexose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase gene (H6PD) located on chromosome 1p36.

Cystathioninuria is a type of autosomal recessive disease and an amino acid metabolic disorder that is characterized by elevated plasma and urinary cystathionine levels. It is caused by autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding cystathionine gamma-lyase (CTH) on chromosome 1p31. This condition is also known as cystathionase deficiency, cystathione gamma-lyase deficiency syndrome, and gamma-cystathionase deficiency. These terms are exact synonyms for cystathioninuria, indicating the specific nature of the disorder and its genetic basis.

Brachyolmia amelogenesis imperfecta syndrome (BAS) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a syndrome with a material basis primarily in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by skeletal dysplasia, including features such as broad ilia, elongated femoral necks with coxa valga, scoliosis, and mild platyspondyly, alongside short trunked short stature and amelogenesis imperfecta. The condition results from autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the latent transforming growth factor beta-binding protein 3 gene (LTBP3) on chromosome 11q13. BAS is also known by several exact synonyms: DASS, STHAG6, dental anomalies and short stature, platyspondyly with amelogenesis imperfecta, and selective tooth agenesis 5.

Donnai Barrow syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and syndrome that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by facial and ocular abnormalities, sensorineural hearing loss, agenesis of the corpus callosum, variable intellectual disability, and proteinuria. This syndrome has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the LDL receptor-related protein 2 gene (LRP2) on chromosome 2q31. Donnai Barrow syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms including DBS/FOAR syndrome, FOAR syndrome, Holmes-Schepens syndrome, diaphragmatic hernia, exomphalos, absent corpus callosum, hypertelorism, myopia, sensorineural deafness, and proteinuria, diaphragmatic hernia-exomphalos-hypertelorism syndrome, diaphragmatic hernia-hypertelorism-myopia-deafness syndrome, facio-oculo-acoustico-renal syndrome, faciooculoacousticorenal syndrome, and syndrome of ocular and facial anomalies, telecanthus and deafness.

Dopamine beta hydroxylase deficiency is a type of inherited metabolic disorder, nervous system disease, and it is associated with symptoms such as ptosis. It is characterized by a disease that has its basis in some structural variant and has its location in the nervous system. The condition is defined as an inherited metabolic disorder marked by decreased beta-hydroxylation of dopamine in nerves, leading to impaired autonomic noradrenergic neurotransmission. Clinical features include severely decreased norepinephrine levels, orthostatic hypotension, ptosis, nasal stuffiness, and delayed eye opening. This disorder is a result of autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the dopamine beta-hydroxylase gene (DBH) on chromosome 9q34. Dopamine beta hydroxylase deficiency is also known by its exact synonyms: congenital dopamine beta-hydroxylase deficiency, noradrenaline deficiency, and norepinephrine deficiency.

3 Methylglutaconic aciduria type 5 is a specific form of 3 methylglutaconic aciduria and an autosomal recessive disease, characterized by at least having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by a 3-methylglutaconic aciduria that results from a homozygous mutation in the DNAJC19 gene located on chromosome 3q26. The disease is also known by several exact synonyms, including 3-methylglutaconic aciduria type V, DCMA, DCMA syndrome, MGA5, MGCA5, and dilated cardiomyopathy with ataxia.

3 Methylglutaconic aciduria with deafness, encephalopathy, and Leigh-like syndrome is a specific condition that falls under several categories. It is a type of autosomal recessive disease, as well as a form of 3 methylglutaconic aciduria, and it is linked to a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is defined by a 3-methylglutaconic aciduria that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SERAC1 gene located on chromosome 6q25. Furthermore, it is also known by several exact synonyms, including 3-methylglutaconic aciduria type 6, MEGDEL, MEGDEL syndrome, and MGCA6.

3 Methylglutaconic aciduria type 1 is a specific type of 3 methylglutaconic aciduria, and it also falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. This particular condition is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of 3 methylglutaconic aciduria type 1 is a 3-methylglutaconic aciduria that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the AUH gene located on chromosome 9q22. Furthermore, 3 methylglutaconic aciduria type 1 is known by several exact synonyms, including 3-methylglutaconic aciduria type I, 3-methylglutaconyl-CoA hydratase deficiency, 3MG-CoA hydratase deficiency, MGA type I, and MGA1.

3 Methylglutaconic aciduria with cataracts, neurologic involvement, and neutropenia is a specific type of 3 methylglutaconic aciduria and an autosomal recessive disease that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is defined by a 3-methylglutaconic aciduria that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CLPB gene on chromosome 11q13. It is also known by several exact synonyms: 3-methylglutaconic aciduria type 7, 3-methylglutaconic aciduria type VII, MEGCANN, MGA7, and MGCA7.

3 Methylglutaconic aciduria type 3 is a type of 3 methylglutaconic aciduria, an autosomal recessive disease, and something that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by a 3-methylglutaconic aciduria that arises from mutations in the OPA3 gene. This condition is known by several exact synonyms, including 3-methylglutaconic aciduria type III, Costeff optic atrophy syndrome, Costeff syndrome, Iraqi-Jewish optic atrophy plus, MGA3, autosomal recessive optic atrophy plus syndrome, autosomal recessive optic atrophy type 3, and infantile optic atrophy with chorea and spastic paraplegia.

Leber congenital amaurosis 9 (LCA9) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of leber congenital amaurosis. It falls under categories of conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and those that have their disease basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. Specifically, LCA9 is defined as a Leber congenital amaurosis that has its material basis in a mutation in the NMNAT1 gene located on chromosome 1p36.

3 Methylglutaconic aciduria type 4 is a type of 3 methylglutaconic aciduria, characterized by mild or intermittent urinary excretion of 3-methylglutaconic acid. It has exact synonyms, including 3-methylglutaconic aciduria type IV, MGA type IV, MGA4, and MGCA4.

Achromatopsia 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is a specific form of achromatopsia. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, Achromatopsia 2 is defined as an achromatopsia that arises due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CNGA3 gene located on chromosome 2q11. Furthermore, Achromatopsia 2 is also known by several exact synonyms, including ACHM2, RMCH2, rod monochromacy 2, and rod monochromatism 2.

Achromatopsia 3 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of achromatopsia. It is categorized as something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Its definition highlights that it results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CNGB3 gene on chromosome 8q2. Moreover, Achromatopsia 3 is known by several exact synonyms, including ACHM1, ACHM3, Pingelapese blindness, RMCH1, rod monochromacy 1, and rod monochromatism 1.

Achromatopsia 7 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, specifically a form of achromatopsia, which fundamentally involves a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an achromatopsia that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ATF6 gene located on chromosome 1q23. Additionally, achromatopsia 7 is exactly synonymous with ACHM7.

Achromatopsia 4 is a type of achromatopsia, defined as an achromatopsia that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GNAT2 gene on chromosome 1p13. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with ACHM4.

Advanced sleep phase syndrome 1 is a type of advanced sleep phase syndrome that is defined as an advanced sleep phase syndrome with a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the PER2 gene on chromosome 2q37. It is exactly synonymous with FASPS1 and familial advanced sleep phase syndrome 1.

Advanced Sleep Phase Syndrome 2 is a specific type of Advanced Sleep Phase Syndrome. It is defined by an advanced sleep phase syndrome that originates from a heterozygous mutation in the CSNK1D gene located on chromosome 17q25. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with both FASPS2 and Familial Advanced Sleep Phase Syndrome 2.

Advanced Sleep Phase Syndrome 3 is a type of Advanced Sleep Phase Syndrome, characterized by a specific heterozygous mutation in the PER3 gene located on chromosome 1p36.23. It is precisely defined as an Advanced Sleep Phase Syndrome with this genetic basis. Furthermore, it is also known by the exact synonyms FASPS3 and Familial Advanced Sleep Phase Syndrome 3.

Age-related macular degeneration 1 is a type of age-related macular degeneration and is defined as an age-related macular degeneration associated with polymorphism in the hemicentin gene (HMCN1) on chromosome 1q25.3-q31.1. It has exact synonyms, including ARMD1 and age-related maculopathy 1.

Age-related macular degeneration 2 (ARMD2) is a type of age-related macular degeneration. It is defined as an age-related macular degeneration conferred by variation in the ABCA4 gene on chromosome 1p22.

Leber congenital amaurosis 2 (LCA2), also known as amaurosis congenita of Leber II, is a type of Leber congenital amaurosis and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from some form of autosomal recessive inheritance and pertains to abnormalities related to prenatal development or birth. Specifically, LCA2 is characterized by night blindness, transient improvement in vision, and eventual progressive visual loss, with its material basis in a mutation in the RPE65 gene on chromosome 1.
Age-related macular degeneration 4 is a type of age-related macular degeneration, which is conferred by variation in the CFH gene on chromosome 1q31. Additionally, it has an exact synonym, ARMD4.

Age-related macular degeneration 6 is a type of age-related macular degeneration. It is defined as an age-related macular degeneration conferred by heterozygous mutation in the RAXL1 gene on chromosome 19p13. Additionally, age-related macular degeneration 6 has the exact synonym ARMD6.

Age-related macular degeneration 7 is a type of age-related macular degeneration, which is defined as an age-related macular degeneration conferred by variation in the HTRA1 gene on chromosome 10q26. Additionally, it has the exact synonym ARMD7.

Age-related macular degeneration 8 is a type of age-related macular degeneration. It is defined as an age-related macular degeneration that has a material basis in mutation in the ARMS2 gene, originally designated LOC387715, on chromosome 10q26. Age-related macular degeneration 8 is exactly synonymous with ARMD8.
Age-related macular degeneration 9 is a type of age-related macular degeneration characterized by a variation in the C3 gene located on chromosome 19p13. It has the exact synonym ARMD9.

Age-related macular degeneration 10 is a type of age-related macular degeneration that is associated with variation in the genomic region 9:112,100,000-127,500,000 (GRCh38), with TLR4 being proposed as a candidate gene. It is also exactly synonymous with ARMD10.

Age related macular degeneration 11 (ARMD11) is a type of age related macular degeneration. It is defined as an age-related macular degeneration conferred by variation in the CST3 gene on chromosome 20p11.

Age related macular degeneration 12 is a type of age related macular degeneration and it is defined as an age related macular degeneration conferred by mutation in the CX3CR1 gene on chromosome 3p22. Additionally, it has the exact synonym ARMD12.

Age-related macular degeneration 13 is a type of age-related macular degeneration, which is defined as an age-related macular degeneration conferred by heterozygous mutation in the CFI gene on chromosome 4q25. Furthermore, it has the exact synonym ARMD13.

Age related macular degeneration 14 is a type of age related macular degeneration and has an exact synonym, ARMD14. It is defined as an age-related macular degeneration associated with variation at or near the C2 and CFB genes on chromosome 6p21.

Age-related macular degeneration 15 is a type of age-related macular degeneration, which is defined as an age-related macular degeneration conferred by variation in the C9 gene on chromosome 5p13. Additionally, it has the exact synonym ARMD15.

Age related macular degeneration 5 is a type of age related macular degeneration. It is defined as an age-related macular degeneration conferred by a heterozygous mutation in the ERCC6 gene on chromosome 10q11. Additionally, age related macular degeneration 5 is exactly synonymous with ARMD5.

Alpha thalassemia intellectual disability syndrome type 1 is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome and also a type of alpha thalassemia. It is defined as an alpha thalassemia that has a material basis in a deletion in chromosome 16p, involving the alpha-1 (HBA1) and alpha-2 (HBA2) genes, among others. This condition is characterized by being an intersection of entities that have at least a material basis in some deletion and entities that have at least a material basis in some chromosome. It is known by various exact synonyms, including ATR syndrome linked to chromosome 16, ATR syndrome, deletion type, ATR-16 syndrome, alpha thalassemia-intellectual disability syndrome, deletion type, alpha thalassemia-retardation syndrome, alpha-thalassemia-intellectual disability syndrome linked to chromosome 16, alpha-thalassemia/mental retardation syndrome, deletion-type, and alpha-thalassemia/mental retardation syndrome, type 1.

Alpha thalassemia X-linked intellectual disability syndrome is a type of X-linked dominant disease and a type of alpha thalassemia. It is a form of something that at least has a material basis in some X-linked dominant inheritance. This syndrome is defined as an alpha thalassemia that has its material basis in mutation in the ATRX gene on Xq21. Furthermore, it has exact synonyms including ATR, nondeletion type, ATR-X syndrome, and alpha-thalassemia/mental retardation syndrome nondeletion type.

Hemoglobin H disease is a type of alpha thalassemia defined as an alpha thalassemia that has its material basis in contiguous gene deletion of the hemoglobin alpha-1 (HBA1) and alpha-2 (HBA2) genes on one chromosome 16, and a defect, whether deletional or nondeletional, in either HBA1 or HBA2 on the other chromosome. The disease is exactly synonymous with several terms including HBH, alpha thalassemia, haemoglobin H type, alpha thalassemia, hemoglobin H type, alpha-thalassemia intermedia, haemoglobin H disease, haemoglobin H disease, deletional, and hemoglobin H disease, deletional.

Autosomal dominant Alport syndrome is a type of Alport syndrome and a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a type of condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined by an Alport syndrome that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the COL4A3 gene.

Autosomal recessive Alport syndrome is a type of Alport syndrome and a specific category of autosomal recessive disease. It is defined as an Alport syndrome that originates from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the COL4A3 or the COL4A4 gene, both located on chromosome 2q. This condition is also considered a type of disorder that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance.

X-linked Alport syndrome is a type of Alport syndrome and also a type of X-linked dominant disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in some X-linked dominant inheritance. An Alport syndrome that specifically has its material basis in the mutation in the gene encoding the alpha-5 chain of basement membrane collagen type IV (COL4A5). Additionally, it has an exact synonym, which is nephropathy and deafness, X-linked.

Alzheimer's disease 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also a type of Alzheimer's disease, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by an association of the apolipoprotein E E4 allele and has several exact synonyms including AD2, Alzheimer disease 2, late onset, Alzheimer disease associated with APOE4, and Alzheimer disease-2.

Alzheimer's disease 16 is a type of Alzheimer's disease that is characterized by an association with a risk allele in the PCDH11X gene on chromosome Xq21.3. Furthermore, it has exact synonyms AD16 and Alzheimer's disease 16, late onset.

Alzheimer's disease 5 is a type of Alzheimer's disease and a form of autosomal dominant disease. It specifically falls under a category of conditions that have a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This particular disease is characterized by an association with variation in the region 12p11.23-q13.12. Alzheimer's disease 5 is exactly synonymous with AD5, Alzheimer disease 5, Alzheimer disease, familial 5, and Alzheimer's disease 5, late onset.

Alzheimer's disease 6 is a type of Alzheimer's disease, which is characterized by an association with variation in the region 10q24. It has exact synonyms including AD6, Alzheimer disease 6, and Alzheimer disease 6, late onset.

Alzheimer's disease 7 is a type of Alzheimer's disease that is characterized by an association with variation in the region 10p13. It has several exact synonyms, including AD7, Alzheimer disease 7, and Alzheimer disease, familial 7.

Alzheimer's disease 4 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and is also classified under Alzheimer's disease. It is associated with autosomal dominant inheritance and is defined specifically as an Alzheimer's disease that has its material basis in a mutation in the presenilin-2 gene (PSEN2) on chromosome 1q42. This condition is exactly synonymous with AD4, Alzheimer disease 4, Alzheimer disease, familial4, and Alzheimer's disease 4, early onset.

Alzheimer's disease 8 is a type of Alzheimer's disease, which is characterized by an association with variation in the region 20p12.2-q11.21. It has exact synonyms including AD8, Alzheimer disease 8, Alzheimer disease, familial 8, and Alzheimer's disease 8, late onset.

Alzheimer's disease 3 is a type of Alzheimer's disease and an autosomal dominant disease, stemming from a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is specifically defined as an Alzheimer's disease that has its material basis in a mutation in the presenilin-1 gene (PSEN1) on chromosome 14q24. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with AD3, Alzheimer disease 3, Alzheimer disease 3, early onset, and Alzheimer disease familial 3.

Alzheimer's disease 10 is a type of Alzheimer's disease characterized by an association with variation in the region 7q36. It is exactly synonymous with AD10, Alzheimer disease 10, Alzheimer disease familial 10, and Alzheimer's disease 10, early onset.

Alzheimer's Disease 11 is a type of Alzheimer's Disease characterized by an association with variation in the region 9p22.1. It has exact synonyms including AD11, Alzheimer Disease 11, and Alzheimer's Disease 11, late onset.

Alzheimer's disease 12 is a type of Alzheimer's disease characterized by an association with variation in the region 8p12-q22. It has exact synonyms including AD12, Alzheimer disease 12, and Alzheimer disease familial 12.

Alzheimer's disease 13 is a type of Alzheimer's disease that is defined as an Alzheimer's disease associated with variation in the region 1q21. It has exact synonyms AD13, Alzheimer disease 13, and Alzheimer's disease 13, late onset.

Alzheimer's disease 14 is a type of Alzheimer's disease that is characterized by an association with variation in the region 1q25. It has several exact synonyms, including AD14, Alzheimer disease 14, and Alzheimer's disease 14, late onset.

Alzheimer's disease 15 is a type of Alzheimer's disease characterized by variations in the region 3q22-q24. It is exactly synonymous with AD15, Alzheimer disease 15, and Alzheimer's disease 15, late onset.

Alzheimer's disease 17 is a type of Alzheimer's disease that is specifically characterized by an association with mutations in the gene TREM2. It is exactly synonymous with AD17, Alzheimer disease 17, and Alzheimer disease 17, late onset.

Alzheimer's disease 18 is a type of Alzheimer's disease, which is defined as an Alzheimer's disease that has a material basis in a mutation in the ADAM10 gene on chromosome 15q21. It is exactly synonymous with AD18, Alzheimer disease 18, and Alzheimer's disease 18, late onset.

Alzheimer's disease 19 is a type of Alzheimer's disease characterized by associated variants of the gene PLD3. It is exactly synonymous with AD19, Alzheimer disease 19, and Alzheimer disease 19 late onset.

Amelogenesis imperfecta type 1b is a form of amelogenesis imperfecta and is classified as an autosomal dominant disease. It specifically arises from a heterozygous mutation in the enamelin gene (ENAM) located on chromosome 4q13. This condition exemplifies a type of disorder that has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is known by several exact synonyms, including AI1B, AIH2, amelogenesis imperfecta type IB, autosomal dominant hypoplastic local amelogenesis imperfecta, and hereditary localized enamel hypoplasia.

Amelogenesis Imperfecta Type 4 (AI4), which also has the exact synonyms AIHHT and Amelogenesis Imperfecta Hypomaturation-Hypoplastic Type with Taurodontism, is a specific form of Amelogenesis Imperfecta. This condition is categorized as an autosomal dominant disease and is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, AI4 can have its material basis in a mutation in the DLX3 gene.

Amelogenesis imperfecta type 1a (AI1A), also known exactly as amelogenesis imperfecta hypoplastic type IA and amelogenesis imperfecta type IA, is a specific type of autosomal dominant disease and a form of amelogenesis imperfecta. It is characterized by a type of condition that inherently involves autosomal dominant inheritance. This disease is defined by an amelogenesis imperfecta that results from a heterozygous mutation in the beta-3 laminin gene (LAMB3) located on chromosome 1q32.

Amelogenesis imperfecta type 3a is a type of autosomal dominant disease, and it specifically falls under amelogenesis imperfecta type 3. Cataract 40 is a type of X-linked monogenic disease, as well as a type of cataract, and it is classified as something that at least has a material basis in some X-linked inheritance. It is defined as a cataract that has its material basis in a mutation in the NHS gene on chromosome Xp22. Additionally, Cataract 40 is exactly synonymous with CTRCT40, cataract 40 X-linked, and cataract 40 with or without microcornea.

Autosomal dominant limb girdle muscular dystrophy is a type of autosomal dominant disease, limb girdle muscular dystrophy, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy is a type of disease that falls under several categories: it is a type of autosomal recessive disease, a type of limb girdle muscular dystrophy, and a type of condition that has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Furthermore, it is defined as a limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2A is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy defined as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding the proteolytic enzyme calpain-3 (CAPN3) on chromosome 15q15. It has several exact synonyms including LGMD2A, Leyden-Moebius muscular dystrophy, limb-girdle muscular dystrophy due to calpain deficiency, muscular dystrophy, limb-girdle, type 2A, pelvofemoral muscular dystrophy, and primary calpainopathy.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2B is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy that is defined as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy with a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding the skeletal muscle protein dysferlin (DYSF) on chromosome 2p13. This condition is exactly synonymous with LGMD2B, LGMD3, limb-girdle muscular dystrophy due to dysferlin deficiency, and limb-girdle muscular dystrophy type 3.
