text: Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2C is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy. It is defined as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the gamma-sarcoglycan gene (SGCG) on chromosome 13q12. This condition is also known by several exact synonyms including DMDA1, LGMD2C, Maghrebian myopathy, SCARMD, autosomal recessive Duchenne-like muscular dystrophy type 1, deficiency of sarcoglycan gamma, gamma-sarcoglycanopathy, limb-girdle muscular dystrophy due to gamma-sarcoglycan deficiency, muscular dystrophy, limb-girdle, type 2C, and severe childhood autosomal recessive muscular dystrophy North African type.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2D is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy. It is defined as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the alpha-sarcoglycan gene (SGCA) on chromosome 17q. This condition is also exactly synonymous with several terms including Alpha-sarcoglycanopathy, DMDA2, Duchenne-like autosomal recessive muscular dystrophy type 2, LGMD2D, muscular dystrophy, limb-girdle, type 2D, and primary adhalinopathy.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2E is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy. This specific disorder is defined as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding beta-sarcoglycan (SGCB) on chromosome 4q12. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including Beta-sarcoglycanopathy, LGMD2E, Limb-girdle muscular dystrophy due to beta-sarcoglycan deficiency, and muscular dystrophy, limb-girdle, type 2E.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2F is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy. It is defined as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has its material basis in mutation in the sarcoglycan-delta gene (SGCD). Furthermore, it has exact synonyms including LGMD2F, delta-sarcoglycanopathy, and limb-girdle muscular dystrophy due to delta-sarcoglycan deficiency.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2G is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy with a definition that specifies it as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy, which has its material basis in a mutation in the gene encoding telethonin (TCAP). It has exact synonyms including LGMD2G, limb-girdle muscular dystrophy due to telethonin deficiency, and muscular dystrophy, limb-girdle, type 2G.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2H, which is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy, is defined as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has a material basis in mutation in the gene encoding tripartite motif-containing protein-32 (TRIM32) on chromosome 9q. It is precisely synonymous with LGMD2H, limb-girdle muscular dystrophy due to TRIM32 deficiency, muscular dystrophy Hutterite type, and sarcotubular myopathy.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2J is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy, which is defined as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the titin gene (TTN). It has exact synonyms, including LGMD2J and muscular dystrophy, limb-girdle, type 2J.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2L is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy, defined as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ANO5 gene on chromosome 11p14. It is exactly synonymous with LGMD2L and muscular dystrophy, limb-girdle, type 2L.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2Q is a specific type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy. It is defined as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the PLEC1 gene. Furthermore, this condition is exactly synonymous with LGMD2Q, autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy due to plectin deficiency, and muscular dystrophy, limb-girdle, type 2Q.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2S is a specific form of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy. It is defined as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that arises due to a homozygous mutation in the TRAPPC11 gene located on chromosome 4q35. Additionally, this condition is exactly synonymous with LGMD2S and muscular dystrophy, limb-girdle, type 2S.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2W is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy. It is defined as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has its material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the LIM zinc finger domain containing 2 gene (LIMS2) on chromosome 2q14. This condition is exactly synonymous with LGMD2W and muscular dystrophy, limb-girdle, type 2W.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2Y is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy. It is defined as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the TOR1AIP1 gene on chromosome 1q24. This condition is also exactly synonymous with LGMD2Y, autosomal recessive muscular dystrophy due to LAP1B deficiency, autosomal recessive muscular dystrophy due to Torsin-1A-interacting protein 1 deficiency, muscular dystrophy with progressive weakness, distal contractures and rigid spine, and muscular dystrophy, limb-girdle, type 2Y.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2X is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy, which is defined as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the BVES gene on chromosome 6q21. This condition is also exactly synonymous with LGMD2X and muscular dystrophy, limb-girdle, type 2X.

Leber congenital amaurosis 10 (LCA10) is a type of monogenic disease and also a specific form of Leber congenital amaurosis. It is characterized as a condition that has its basis in some abnormalities of prenatal development or birth, as well as in gene-related issues. LCA10 is defined as a Leber congenital amaurosis characterized by severe infantile-onset cone-rod dystrophy with high hyperopia and severe electroretinogram (ERG) abnormalities, which is caused by a mutation in the CEP290 gene located on chromosome 12q21.32. Additionally, LCA10 is exactly synonymous with LCA10, indicating its specific identification within the spectrum of Leber congenital amaurosis.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2O is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy. It is defined as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the gene encoding protein O-mannose beta-1,2-N-acetylglucosaminyltransferase (POMGNT1) on chromosome 1p34. Additionally, autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2O is exactly synonymous with LGMD2O, MDDGC3, muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy (limb-girdle) type C3, and muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy limb-girdle POMGNT1-related.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2p is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy that is defined as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy, which has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the gene encoding alpha-dystroglycan (DAG1) on chromosome 3p21. Moreover, this condition is precisely synonymous with LGMD2P, MDDGC9, muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy (limb-girdle) type C9, and muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy limb-girdle DAG1-related.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2T is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy. It is defined as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GMPPB gene encoding the beta subunit of GDP-mannose pyrophosphorylase on chromosome 3p21. This condition is also known by several exact synonyms including LGMD2T, MDDGC14, muscular dystrophy limb-girdle type 2T, muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy (limb-girdle) type C14, and muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy limb-girdle GMPPB-related.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2u is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy, defined as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the ISPD gene on chromosome 7p21. It is exactly synonymous with LGMD2U, MDDGC7, autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy due to ISPD deficiency, muscular dystrophy limb-girdle type 2U, and muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy (limb-girdle) type C7.

Autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy type 2M is a type of autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that is defined by an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy with a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding fukutin (FKTN) on chromosome 9q31. This condition is exactly synonymous with LGMD2M, MDDGC4, and muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy (limb-girdle) type C 4.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2K is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy. It is defined as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding protein O-mannosyltransferase (POMT1). Furthermore, autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2K is exactly synonymous with LGMD2K, MDDGC1, limb-girdle muscular dystrophy-intellectual disability syndrome, muscular dystrophy limb-girdle type 2K, and muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy (limb-girdle) type C 1.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2n is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy, defined as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the POMT2 gene on chromosome 14q24.3. It is exactly synonymous with LGMD2N, MDDGC2, muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy (limb-girdle) type C 2, and muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy limb-girdle POMT2-related.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2I is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy, which is defined as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding fukutin-related protein (FKRP) on chromosome 19q13.3. This condition is also precisely known by several exact synonyms including LGMD2I, Limb-girdle muscular dystrophy due to FKRP deficiency, MDDGC5, muscular dystrophy limb-girdle type 2I, muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy (limb-girdle) type C 5, and muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy limb-girdle FRKP-related.

Autosomal dominant limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 1H is a type of autosomal dominant limb girdle muscular dystrophy with a definition that specifies it as an autosomal dominant limb-girdle muscular dystrophy having its material basis in a variation in the region 3p25.1-p23. Moreover, it has exact synonyms including LGMD1H and muscular dystrophy limb-girdle type 1H.

Autosomal dominant limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2 is a type of autosomal dominant limb girdle muscular dystrophy. It is defined as an autosomal dominant limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TNPO3 gene on chromosome 7q32. Furthermore, it has exact synonyms including LGMD1F, autosomal dominant limb-girdle muscular dystrophy type 1F, and muscular dystrophy limb-girdle type 1F.

Autosomal dominant limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 1 is a type of autosomal dominant limb girdle muscular dystrophy. It is defined as an autosomal dominant limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the DNAJB6 gene on chromosome 7q36. This condition is also exactly synonymous with LGMD1D, autosomal dominant limb-girdle muscular dystrophy type 1E, muscular dystrophy limb-girdle type 1D, and muscular dystrophy limb-girdle type 1E.

Autosomal dominant limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 3 is a specific type of autosomal dominant limb girdle muscular dystrophy. It is defined as an autosomal dominant limb-girdle muscular dystrophy that arises from heterozygous mutations in the HNRNPDL gene located on chromosome 4q21. This condition is also precisely known as LGMD1G, autosomal dominant limb-girdle muscular dystrophy type 1G, and muscular dystrophy limb-girdle type 1G.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 1 is a type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, which is defined by a familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the MYH7 gene on chromosome 14q12. It is exactly synonymous with CMH1, cardiomyopathy, familial hypertrophic 1, and hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 19.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 2 is a type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, and it is defined as a familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the cardiac troponin-T2 gene (TNNT2). Additionally, hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 2 is exactly synonymous with CMH2 and cardiomyopathy familial hypertrophic 2.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 3 is a type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, defined as a familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the alpha-tropomyosin gene (TPM1) on chromosome 15q22. It is also exactly synonymous with CMH3 and cardiomyopathy familial hypertrophic 3.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 4 is a type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy and is defined as a familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that has its material basis in heterozygous, homozygous, or compound heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding cardiac myosin-binding protein C (MYBPC3) on chromosome 11p11. Additionally, it has the exact synonyms CMH4 and cardiomyopathy, familial hypertrophic, 4.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 21 is a type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy and has the definition of being a familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy associated with having a material basis in region 7p12.1-q21 variation. It is exactly synonymized as CMH21 and cardiomyopathy familial hypertrophic 21.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 6 is a type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that is defined by a familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy with a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding the gamma-2 regulatory subunit of AMP-activated protein kinase (PRKAG2). It is exactly synonymous with both CMH6 and cardiomyopathy, familial hypertrophic 6.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 7 is a type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, which is defined as a familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TNNI3 gene on chromosome 19q13.4. Additionally, it has exact synonyms including CMH7 and cardiomyopathy, familial hypertrophic 7.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 8 is a specific type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. It is characterized by a familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that has a material basis in homozygous or heterozygous mutation in the MYL3 gene. Additionally, hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 8 is exactly synonymous with cardiomyopathy hypertrophic mid-left ventricular chamber type 1 and cardiomyopathy, familial hypertrophic, 8.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 9 is a type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, which is defined as a familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TTN gene on chromosome 2q31. It is exactly synonymous with CMH9 and cardiomyopathy, familial hypertrophic, 9.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 10 is a type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, which is defined as a familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that has a material basis in mutation in the MYL2 gene. It is exactly synonymous with CMH10 and cardiomyopathy, familial hypertrophic, 10.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 11 is a type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy and is defined as a familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ACTC1 gene on chromosome 15q14. It also has the exact synonyms CMH11 and cardiomyopathy familial hypertrophic 11.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 12 is a type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, which is defined as a familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the CSRP3 gene on chromosome 11p15. It is also exactly synonymous with CMH12 and cardiomyopathy familial hypertrophic 12.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 13 is a type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy and it is defined as a familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TNNC1 gene on chromosome 3p21. It also has exact synonyms, including CMH13 and cardiomyopathy familial hypertrophic 13.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 14 is a type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, which is defined as a familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that has its material basis in mutation in the MYH6 gene. It is also exactly synonymous with CMH14 and cardiomyopathy familial hypertrophic 14.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 15 is a type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, which is defined as a familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the vinculin gene (VCL) on chromosome 10q22. Moreover, it is exactly synonymous with CMH15 and cardiomyopathy familial hypertrophic 15.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 16 is a type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy and it is defined as a familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the MYOZ2 gene located on chromosome 4q26. Additionally, hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 16 is exactly synonymous with CMH16 and cardiomyopathy familial hypertrophic 16.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 17 is a type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, and it is defined as a familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the junctophilin gene (JPH2) on chromosome 20q12. It is also exactly synonymous with CMH17 and cardiomyopathy familial hypertrophic 17.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 18 is a type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, defined as a familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding phospholamban (PLN) on chromosome 6q22.1. It is also exactly synonymous with CMH18 and cardiomyopathy familial hypertrophic 18.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 20 is a type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy and it is defined as a familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the NEXN gene on chromosome 1p31.1. Additionally, hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 20 is precisely referred to by the exact synonyms CMH20 and cardiomyopathy familial hypertrophic 20.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 26 is a type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy and is defined by a familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the FLNC gene on chromosome 7q32. It also has the exact synonyms CMH26 and cardiomyopathy familial hypertrophic 26.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy 25 is a type of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, which is defined as a familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the TCAP gene on chromosome 17q12. It is also exactly synonymous with CMH25 and cardiomyopathy familial hypertrophic 25.

Leber Congenital Amaurosis 6 (LCA6) is a type of Leber Congenital Amaurosis and an autosomal recessive disease that has its material basis in a mutation in the RPGRIP1 gene located on chromosome 14q11. It is characterized by traits such as early photophobia, hypermetropia less than +7 diopters, and visual acuity ranging from 20/400 to the ability to count fingers. Additionally, LCA6 is associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth due to its autosomal recessive inheritance.

Leber Congenital Amaurosis 13 (LCA13) is a type of Leber Congenital Amaurosis, which is characterized by mild or absent hyperopia, transient improvement of visual acuity, and eventual macular atrophy with severe disease progression. This condition has its material basis in a mutation in the RDH12 gene located on chromosome 14q23.3. It is classified as both an autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive disease, indicating that it can be inherited in either manner. Furthermore, LCA13 has a material basis that is at least partly grounded in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth, encompassing traits of both autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive inheritance patterns.

Leber Congenital Amaurosis 3 (LCA3) is a type of monogenic disease and a specific form of Leber Congenital Amaurosis. It is characterized by conditions that stem from abnormalities in prenatal development or birth and has a genetic basis. Specifically, LCA3 has a material basis in a mutation in the SPATA7 gene located on chromosome 14q31. Additionally, it is also referred to by its exact synonym, LCA3.

Leber Congenital Amaurosis 4 (LCA4) is a type of Leber Congenital Amaurosis and an autosomal recessive disease, which implies it at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by a relatively severe phenotype, manifesting a range of symptoms including maculopathy, marked bone-spicule pigmentary retinopathy in most cases, and keratoconus and cataract in a large subset. This condition has a genetic basis in a mutation in the AIPL1 gene on chromosome 17p13. Furthermore, LCA4 is associated with phenotypes such as retinopathy and keratoconus, and it can be linked to abnormalities in prenatal development or birth.

Leber congenital amaurosis 7 is a type of monogenic disease and a specific form of Leber congenital amaurosis. It is categorized under diseases that have their basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth, and its origin is rooted in genetic abnormalities. Specifically, Leber congenital amaurosis 7 is defined as a Leber congenital amaurosis that has its material basis in a mutation in the CRX gene located on chromosome 19q13. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with LCA7.

Osteogenesis imperfecta type 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and osteogenesis imperfecta, which means it is something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by bone fragility and blue sclerae and has its material basis in dominantly inherited mutations in the COL1A1 gene on chromosome 17q21.33 or the COL1A2 gene on chromosome 7q21.3. Additionally, it has exact synonyms OI1 and osteogenesis imperfecta type I.

Osteogenesis imperfecta with opalescent teeth, blue sclerae, and wormian bones, but without fractures, is a type of osteogenesis imperfecta. This particular osteogenesis imperfecta, found in a single South African family, is defined by these specific characteristics.

Osteogenesis imperfecta type 8 is a form of osteogenesis imperfecta and an autosomal recessive disease, which inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by a mutation in the P3H1 gene located on chromosome 1p34.2. Osteogenesis imperfecta type 8 is precisely synonymous with OI8 and osteogenesis imperfecta type VIII.

Osteogenesis imperfecta type 7 (OI7), also known exactly as osteogenesis imperfecta type VII, is a specific type of osteogenesis imperfecta and an autosomal recessive disease. It is categorized under conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is defined by having a material basis in mutations in the CRTAP gene located on chromosome 3p22.

Osteogenesis imperfecta type 17 (OI17), also known exactly as osteogenesis imperfecta type XVII, is a specific form of osteogenesis imperfecta. It is characterized as an autosomal recessive disease that fundamentally arises from mutations in the SPARC gene located on chromosome 5q33. This condition exemplifies a type of disorder that inherently possesses a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance.

Osteogenesis imperfecta type 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of osteogenesis imperfecta, which is characterized by its basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an osteogenesis imperfecta that is marked by progressive limb and spinal deformity, along with normal sclerae, and arises from mutations in the COL1A1 gene on chromosome 17q21.33 or the COL1A2 gene on chromosome 7q21.3. Additionally, osteogenesis imperfecta type 3 is precisely known as OI3, osteogenesis imperfecta type III, and progressively deforming osteogenesis imperfecta with normal sclera.

Osteogenesis imperfecta type 4, also known precisely as OI4, osteogenesis imperfecta type IV, and osteogenesis imperfecta with normal sclera, is a subtype of osteogenesis imperfecta and an autosomal dominant disease. It is defined by its bone fragility and normal sclerae, resulting from dominantly inherited mutations in the COL1A1 gene on chromosome 17q21.33 or the COL1A2 gene on chromosome 7q21.3. Additionally, this condition is categorized as having a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Osteogenesis imperfecta type 2, also known exactly as OI2, Vrolik type of osteogenesis imperfecta, osteogenesis imperfecta type II, and perinatal lethal osteogenesis imperfecta congenita, is a type of osteogenesis imperfecta and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by bone fragility and perinatal lethality, with its material basis being dominantly inherited mutations in the COL1A1 gene on chromosome 17q21.33 or the COL1A2 gene on chromosome 7q21.3. Additionally, this condition is a type of disorder that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Osteogenesis imperfecta type 13, which has exact synonyms OI13 and osteogenesis imperfecta type XIII, is a type of osteogenesis imperfecta and an autosomal recessive disease. It specifically has its material basis in a mutation in the BMP1 gene on chromosome 8p21, indicating that it is a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance.

Osteogenesis imperfecta type 14 is a type of monogenic disease and a specific form of osteogenesis imperfecta, characterized as a disease that has its basis in genetic mutations. Specifically, it is defined by having a material basis in mutation in the TMEM38B gene located on chromosome 9q31. Additionally, osteogenesis imperfecta type 14 is exactly synonymous with OI14 and osteogenesis imperfecta type XIV.

Osteogenesis imperfecta type 5 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of osteogenesis imperfecta, which is characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined by a mutation in the IFITM5 gene located on chromosome 11p15. Additionally, osteogenesis imperfecta type 5 is exactly synonymous with OI5 and osteogenesis imperfecta type V.

Osteogenesis imperfecta type 16 is a type of osteogenesis imperfecta characterized by having a material basis in contiguous gene deletion on chromosome 11p11. It is exactly synonymous with OI16, chromosome 11p11.2 deletion syndrome 91.3-KB, and osteogenesis imperfecta type XVI.

Osteogenesis imperfecta type 10 is a type of osteogenesis imperfecta and an autosomal recessive disease, which means it is a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This specific form of osteogenesis imperfecta is defined by having a material basis in a mutation in the SERPINH gene located on chromosome 11q13. Additionally, osteogenesis imperfecta type 10 has exact synonyms, including OI10 and osteogenesis imperfecta type X.

Osteogenesis imperfecta type 15 is a type of osteogenesis imperfecta and an autosomal recessive disease, which is a category of something that has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by an osteogenesis imperfecta that has its material basis in a mutation in the WNT1 gene on chromosome 12q13. Furthermore, osteogenesis imperfecta type 15 has the exact synonyms OI15 and osteogenesis imperfecta type XV.

Osteogenesis imperfecta type 12 is a type of osteogenesis imperfecta and an autosomal recessive disease, which specifically has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by having a material basis in a mutation in the SP7 gene located on chromosome 12q13. Additionally, osteogenesis imperfecta type 12 is exactly synonymous with OI12 and osteogenesis imperfecta type XII.

Osteogenesis imperfecta type 9, which is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of osteogenesis imperfecta, has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as an osteogenesis imperfecta that has a material basis in a mutation in the PPIB gene on chromosome 15q22. Additionally, this condition is exactly synonymous with OI9 and osteogenesis imperfecta type IX.

Osteogenesis imperfecta type 6 is a type of monogenic disease and also a type of osteogenesis imperfecta, indicating that it is a disease with a basis in some gene. It is specifically defined as an osteogenesis imperfecta that has a material basis in a mutation in the SERPINF1 gene on chromosome 17p13.3. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with OI6 and osteogenesis imperfecta type VI.

Osteogenesis imperfecta type 11 is a type of osteogenesis imperfecta and an autosomal recessive disease, which specifically has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by a mutation in the FKBP10 gene located on chromosome 17q21. Osteogenesis imperfecta type 11 is exactly synonymous with OI11 and osteogenesis imperfecta type XI.
